# C. 2 Discussions on 2SLS with $\ell_{2}$-Regularization 

In this section, we briefly discuss a generalization of our analysis to the case where the 2SLS estimator is regularized by the $\ell_{2}$ penalty (Ridge 2SLS). For this case, the bi-level optimization problem (6) is modified as follows:

$$
\begin{aligned}
\min _{\boldsymbol{\beta}} & \mathcal{L}(\boldsymbol{\beta})=\frac{1}{n} \sum_{i=1}^{n}\left(y_{i}-\boldsymbol{z}_{i}^{\top} \boldsymbol{\Theta} \boldsymbol{\beta}\right)^{2}+\frac{1}{2} \lambda\|\boldsymbol{\beta}\|^{2} \\
\text { where } & \hat{\boldsymbol{\Theta}}:=\underset{\boldsymbol{\Theta}}{\arg \min } \quad \frac{1}{n} \sum_{j=1}^{n}\left(\boldsymbol{x}_{j}-\boldsymbol{z}_{j}^{\top} \boldsymbol{\Theta}\right)^{2}+\frac{1}{2} \tau\|\boldsymbol{\Theta}\|_{F}^{2}
\end{aligned}
$$

where $\lambda, \tau \geq 0$ are regularization parameters. To solve this problem, the GD updates in (7) is modified as follows:

$$
\begin{aligned}
\boldsymbol{\Theta}^{(t+1)} & =\boldsymbol{\Theta}^{(t)}-\eta\left[\boldsymbol{Z}^{\top}\left(\boldsymbol{Z} \boldsymbol{\Theta}^{(t)}-\boldsymbol{X}\right)+\tau \boldsymbol{\Theta}^{(t)}\right] \\
\boldsymbol{\beta}^{(t+1)} & =\boldsymbol{\beta}^{(t)}-\alpha\left[\boldsymbol{\Theta}^{(t) \top} \boldsymbol{Z}^{\top}\left(\boldsymbol{Z} \boldsymbol{\Theta}^{(t)} \boldsymbol{\beta}^{(t)}-\boldsymbol{Y}\right)+\lambda \boldsymbol{\beta}^{(t)}\right]
\end{aligned}
$$

The only difference between (7) and (61) is the additional terms $\tau \boldsymbol{\Theta}^{(t)}$ in (61a), and $\lambda \boldsymbol{\beta}^{(t)}$ in (61b). The convergence analysis of the $\ell_{2}$-regularized GD updates in (61) can be conducted in a similar manner as in Theorem 3.1. The only difference is that the convergence rate $\Lambda$ is now determined by the spectral radiuses of $\boldsymbol{I}-\eta\left(\boldsymbol{Z}^{\top} \boldsymbol{Z}+\tau \boldsymbol{I}\right)$ and $\boldsymbol{I}-\alpha\left(\hat{\boldsymbol{\Theta}}^{\top} \boldsymbol{Z}^{\top} \boldsymbol{Z} \hat{\boldsymbol{\Theta}}+\lambda \boldsymbol{I}\right)$, respectively.

With the same configuration as in Theorem 3.2 but adding $p+1$ attention heads in the second layer (i.e. the second layer needs $3 p+3$ heads), we can show that transformers are able to implement the $\ell_{2}$-regularized GD updates in (61). The proof follows directly from Appendix B.2, with the construction of the new attention heads in the second layer as follows.
For $m=2 p+2+k, k=1, \ldots, p$, define $\boldsymbol{Q}_{m}^{(2)}, \boldsymbol{K}_{m}^{(2)}, \boldsymbol{V}_{m}^{(2)}$ such that:

$$
\boldsymbol{Q}_{m}^{(2)} \boldsymbol{h}_{i}^{(1)}=\left[\begin{array}{l}
1 \\
\mathbf{0}
\end{array}\right], \boldsymbol{K}_{m}^{(2)} \boldsymbol{h}_{i}^{(1)}=\left[\begin{array}{l}
1 \\
\mathbf{0}
\end{array}\right], \boldsymbol{V}_{m}^{(2)} \boldsymbol{h}_{i}^{(1)}=-\eta \tau \sum_{l=1}^{q} \Theta_{l k}^{(0)} \boldsymbol{e}_{D_{0}+(k-1) q+l}
$$

For $m=3 p+3$, define $\boldsymbol{Q}_{3 p+3}^{(2)}, \boldsymbol{K}_{3 p+3}^{(2)}, \boldsymbol{V}_{3 p+3}^{(2)}$ such that:

$$
\boldsymbol{Q}_{3 p+3}^{(2)} \boldsymbol{h}_{i}^{(1)}=\left[\begin{array}{l}
1 \\
\mathbf{0}
\end{array}\right], \boldsymbol{K}_{3 p+3}^{(2)} \boldsymbol{h}_{i}^{(1)}=\left[\begin{array}{l}
1 \\
\mathbf{0}
\end{array}\right], \boldsymbol{V}_{3 p+3}^{(2)} \boldsymbol{h}_{i}^{(1)}=-\alpha \lambda \sum_{l=1}^{q} \beta_{l}^{(0)} \boldsymbol{e}_{D_{0}+q p+l}
$$

Then the remaining proof follows exactly the same as Appendix B.2. This result indicates that transformers are potentially capable of handling multicollinearity in IV regression problem. We conduct experiments to validate this and the results are shown in Appendix C.3.
